  "templateId": "emperor-new-clothes-en",
  "language": "en-US",
  "storyTitle": "The Emperor's New Clothes",
  "summary": "Emperor Lorenzo trusts two swindlers who promise invisible cloth, parades in nothing, and learns through a child's honesty that vanity can silence judgment.",
  "storyPlot": "In the year 1710, on a bright summer morning in the kingdom of Fantasia, Emperor Lorenzo was obsessed with new clothes. The sun shone brightly, and the palace gardens were in full bloom. Two swindlers, Marco and Pietro, arrived, claiming they could weave a cloth invisible to fools. The emperor hired them with gold and silk. His trusted old minister Alberto was sent first to inspect; he saw nothing but feared being thought a fool, so he reported the cloth was magnificent. The second assistant, young officer Bruno, also saw nothing but praised its beauty. On the parade day through the city streets, the weather was sunny and warm, and the streets were lined with cheering crowds and colorful banners. The swindlers mimed dressing the emperor in a coat and trousers. Suddenly, a boy, Luca, shouted, \"The emperor has nothing on!\" The truth spread among the crowd. Emperor Lorenzo realized the child was right and felt deep shame. Later that evening, back in the palace, the emperor sat alone in his chamber, which was dimly lit and silent. He felt foolish and humiliated. He finally understood that vanity had made him blind and that only the innocent child had the courage to speak the truth.",
